## Overview
This runbook documents the step-by-step procedure to execute 
a failover from the primary region (us-east-1) to the disaster 
recovery region (us-west-2) in the event of a regional outage.

**RTO Target:** 30 minutes  
**RPO Target:** 5 minutes

---

## Pre-Requisites
Before executing this runbook ensure:
- [ ] AWS Console access is available
- [ ] You have admin permissions on the AWS account
- [ ] us-west-2 VPC and subnets are in place
- [ ] DR VPC peering connection is active
- [ ] RDS read replica exists in us-west-2

---

## Disaster Recovery Steps

### Phase 1 — Declare Incident (5 minutes)

**Step 1 — Confirm Regional Outage**
- Go to https://health.aws.amazon.com
- Confirm us-east-1 is showing an active incident
- Check AWS Status Twitter/X for confirmation
- Do not failover for minor issues — only full regional outages

**Step 2 — Notify Stakeholders**
- Alert your team that failover is being initiated
- Expected downtime: 15-30 minutes
- Document the time failover started

---

### Phase 2 — Database Failover (10 minutes)

**Step 3 — Promote RDS Read Replica**
- Log into AWS Console
- Switch region to **us-west-2**
- Go to **RDS → Databases**
- Select the read replica in us-west-2
- Click **Actions → Promote**
- Confirm promotion
- Wait for status to change to **Available**
- Copy the new **Endpoint URL**

**Step 4 — Update Application Database Connection**
- Note the new RDS endpoint from Step 3
- This will be used when configuring the DR application servers

---

### Phase 3 — Compute Failover (10 minutes)

**Step 5 — Launch EC2 Instances in us-west-2**
- Go to **EC2 → Launch Instance** in us-west-2
- Use the same configuration as main-vpc servers:
  - AMI: Amazon Linux 2023
  - Instance type: t2.micro
  - VPC: dr-vpc
  - Subnet: dr-public-subnet-2a
  - Security group: create equivalent of webserver-sg
- Launch minimum 2 instances

**Step 6 — Install Web Application**
- Connect to each new instance via SSM Session Manager
- Run these commands:
```bash
sudo yum install -y httpd
sudo systemctl start httpd
sudo systemctl enable httpd
```
- Update application configuration to point to new 
  RDS endpoint from Step 3

**Step 7 — Create Load Balancer in us-west-2**
- Go to **EC2 → Load Balancers**
- Create new Application Load Balancer in dr-vpc
- Name: dr-alb
- Add both DR public subnets
- Create target group and register new EC2 instances
- Wait for instances to show healthy

---

### Phase 4 — DNS Cutover (5 minutes)

**Step 8 — Update DNS**
- Go to **Route 53** (or your DNS provider)
- Update the A record to point to the DR load balancer DNS name
- Set TTL to 60 seconds for fast propagation
- Wait 1-2 minutes for DNS to propagate globally

**Step 9 — Verify Application is Working**
- Open a browser and navigate to your application URL
- Confirm the application loads correctly
- Test key functionality (login, data retrieval etc.)
- Confirm data integrity from the promoted RDS instance

---

### Phase 5 — Post-Failover (5 minutes)

**Step 10 — Monitor and Confirm Stability**
- Monitor CloudWatch metrics for error rates
- Check ALB target group health checks
- Confirm all instances showing healthy
- Monitor RDS metrics in us-west-2

**Step 11 — Document the Incident**
Record the following:
- Time incident declared
- Time failover initiated
- Time failover completed
- Actual RTO achieved
- Any data loss (RPO achieved)
- Issues encountered during failover

---

## Failback Procedure (After us-east-1 Recovers)

**Step 1** — Confirm us-east-1 is fully recovered  
**Step 2** — Set up new RDS read replica from us-west-2 
promoted instance back to us-east-1  
**Step 3** — Wait for replication to catch up  
**Step 4** — Switch DNS back to us-east-1 load balancer  
**Step 5** — Verify application working in us-east-1  
**Step 6** — Decommission DR resources to stop billing  

